Pour the @water for the bulgur wheat{220%ml} into a large #saucepan{}, stir in half the
@vegetable stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for
~{1%minute}.

Pop a lid on the saucepan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side
for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once
hot, add the onion and fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the @dried oregano{1%sachet}, @harissa paste{50%g} and garlic. Stir-fry for
~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1%carton}, the remaining @vegetable stock paste{10%g},
the @sugar{1%tsp} and @water for the sauce{150%ml}.

Bring to the boil, then simmer until slightly thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Once your harissa sauce has thickened, add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a
handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Lower the heat to medium and add the @ready to eat falafels{171%g} to the sauce,
carefully stirring to coat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Simmer gently until cooked through, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the @butter{20%g} to the sauce. Stir gently until melted.

Share the bulgur wheat between your #bowls{}, then top with the falafels and
harissa sauce.

Drizzle over the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} to finish.

Enjoy!

> Hailing from Middle Eastern and Levantine cuisine, falafel are a fast favourite
> with vegetarians and meat-eaters alike due to their unique texture and
> versatile flavour. Our Falafels in Harissa Sauce pairs these veggie fritters
> with a punchy spiced sauce atop bulgur wheat with some yoghurt to cool off
> with.